    <title>Combined summary - MtGox blames bitcoin</title>
    <updated>2023-06-08T02:54:26.678463+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2014-February/004313.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>In February 2014, discussions were taking place on the Bitcointalk forum and Bitcoin-development mailing list regarding various issues related to Bitcoin and MtGox. One of the discussions focused on the malleability issue and how it affects fund safety. Participants also talked about whether Bitcoin developers should be pressured by MtGox to include a patch in the source code, with some arguing that venture capitalists were taking money from unsuspecting investors.Additionally, there were conversations about the possibility of a DOS attack and concerns about insider trading by people who make market bets just before information goes public. Some users suggested that businesses could prevent attacks by training customer service representatives to ask customers if their wallet software shows a payment to a specific address of a specific amount at an approximate time. However, the procedure followed by MtGox did not investigate why funds didn't arrive and let front-line customer service reps manually send funds to customers, which was a serious mistake. Another topic discussed was the importance of well-thought-out payment protocols like BIP70 and stealth addresses to prevent possible attack scenarios. Several users discussed the need for independent developers who are not connected to venture capital or investment connections. Gregory Maxwell stated that he could be considered independent but acknowledged that others may exist. Some users suggested that MtGox should release their code under AGPLv3 to allow for public technical discussions on how to fix it while maintaining intellectual property ownership. It was argued that this would cut off a significant revenue stream for market manipulators. In a separate conversation on the Bitcoin Github repository, concerns were raised about individuals with commit access who may have investment connections to those manipulating markets.Meanwhile, Peter Todd suggested unsystem at lists.dyne.org as a better forum for political conversations. He also included an advertisement for the BlackBerry 10.2.1 Runtime for Android apps and provided information on how to get an Android app in front of a new audience.Gavin Andresen, the project lead of Bitcoin, addressed the issue of MtGox trying to blame their problems on Bitcoin and wrote an official statement setting the record straight. He emphasized that although there are issues, MtGox should have worked around them rather than blaming Bitcoin. The technical analysis conducted before the issue indicated that MtGox was at fault for their faulty wallet implementation.Overall, these discussions addressed various issues related to Bitcoin's security and the role of developers in ensuring its safety and success.</summary>
